        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-6">What management research is actually worth doing in 2026</h1>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 pb-6 border-b border-border">
          <div>
            <p class="font-semibold">Prof. Stanley Oliver</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-muted">Director, Doctoral College UK</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Article body -->
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none space-y-6 text-muted">

        <p class="text-lg font-medium text-foreground">There is a question I am asked, in different forms, by almost every doctoral applicant I speak with. It goes something like this: "Is my research topic important enough? Is it the kind of thing that academic journals actually care about?" My answer is always the same: wrong question.</p>

        <p>The better question — the one that should be guiding every practitioner-researcher entering doctoral study in 2026 — is this: does my research have the potential to improve how organisations work, how professionals lead, or how systems serve the people inside them? If the answer is yes, then you are onto something worth doing. Whether any particular journal cares is a secondary consideration.</p>

        <p>I say this not to be dismissive of academic publication. Publication matters. Peer review matters. Contributing to an existing body of literature is a genuine and important obligation for doctoral researchers. But the academic research ecosystem has its own incentive structures, its own fashions, and its own blind spots. And those blind spots are often largest precisely where the most consequential questions live.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8 mb-4">The publication gap in management research</h2>

        <p>Consider the management research landscape as it exists today. Top-tier journals in organisational behaviour, strategic management, and human resource management publish extraordinary work. The methodological sophistication of studies in journals like the Academy of Management Journal or the Strategic Management Journal has increased enormously over the past two decades. Causal identification has improved. Multi-level models have become standard. Longitudinal designs are more common.</p>

        <p>And yet, if you walk into most UK organisations and ask senior leaders which recent piece of academic management research has meaningfully changed how they think about their work, you will often be met with a puzzled silence. This is not because leaders are incurious or anti-intellectual. It is because the questions that academic management research asks — constrained by data availability, methodological fashion, and reviewer expectations — are often not the questions that matter most at the sharp end of practice.</p>

        <p>The questions that matter at the sharp end are messier, more contextual, and harder to generalise. How does a specific type of public sector organisation maintain strategic coherence when its political environment shifts every eighteen months? What actually enables psychological safety in high-pressure professional services firms, as opposed to what the theory says should enable it? How do small and medium-sized enterprises transfer tacit knowledge when they cannot afford formal knowledge management systems?</p>

        <p>These are not trivial questions. They are not questions that resist rigorous inquiry. They are, in fact, exactly the kind of questions that doctoral-level research is well placed to address. But they are questions that academic researchers, working with samples of convenience and under pressure to produce high-frequency, high-generalisability outputs, often cannot or do not pursue.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8 mb-4">The practitioner advantage</h2>

        <p>This is where practitioner-researchers — the people who come to doctoral study with ten, fifteen, or twenty years of senior professional experience — have a genuine, structural advantage over their full-time academic counterparts.</p>

        <p>You have access. You know the context. You can see problems from the inside in a way that no externally-positioned researcher can replicate, however many interviews they conduct. You can observe what actually happens in your organisation as opposed to what people report happens when a researcher is asking. You understand the informal power structures, the cultural norms, the decision-making shortcuts that shape organisational behaviour far more than any formal policy document.</p>

        <p>This access comes with responsibility, of course — ethical obligations around positionality, confidentiality, and the management of dual roles are non-trivial, and I do not want to minimise them. But it also comes with research capacity of enormous value. The insider-researcher, pursuing questions of genuine importance to their own professional context, is not a second-tier version of the academic researcher. They are a different kind of researcher, asking different kinds of questions, with different kinds of access — and the world needs that kind of research.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8 mb-4">What makes management research worth doing</h2>

        <p>So what, specifically, makes management research worth doing in 2026? I would suggest three criteria, none of which require you to predict whether the Journal of Management Studies will publish your work.</p>

        <p><strong>First, the research should be consequential.</strong> It should address a question whose answer has the potential to change something. That something might be a specific organisational practice, a leadership approach, a system design, a professional development programme, or a policy. The question does not need to be world-changing — most valuable research is not. But it should be research that could, if well executed and well communicated, make something work better for someone.</p>

        <p><strong>Second, the research should be grounded in theory, not just experience.</strong> This is where doctoral study earns its distinction from consultancy or reflective practice. Your practitioner experience is the raw material. Theory — the accumulated and tested explanatory frameworks developed by researchers over decades — is what allows you to move from description to understanding, from observation to explanation. Research that connects a specific organisational phenomenon to an existing theoretical framework, extends that framework, or challenges it with evidence from a new context, is research that adds genuine knowledge to the world.</p>

        <p><strong>Third, the research should be honest about its limitations.</strong> Context-specific research is not inferior research. A rigorous case study of leadership in a single NHS Trust is not a lesser contribution than a large-scale quantitative study — it is a different kind of contribution. The failure of practitioner-research is not usually in its scope; it is in the failure to be clear about what the scope is and what conclusions can legitimately be drawn. Be honest about what your research can and cannot tell us, and you will produce work that stands up.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8 mb-4">The question worth asking</h2>

        <p>If you are sitting with a doctoral research idea — an organisational problem you have been thinking about for years, a leadership question that the literature has not fully answered for your context, a system-level puzzle that keeps coming back to you — my invitation is this: do not start by asking whether it is important enough for academia. Start by asking whether it is important enough for your field, your sector, your organisation, the people who will be affected by the knowledge it generates.</p>

        <p>If the answer is yes, then the research is worth doing. The rigour, the theoretical grounding, the methodological care — all of that is learnable. That is what a doctoral programme is for. But the question itself? That has to come from somewhere real. And for practitioner-researchers, real is exactly what you have.</p>

